Introduction

This case study explores Fitbit usage data from 30 users to generate insights that can help Bellabeat better understand user behavior and improve their marketing strategy. We follow the six-step analysis framework: Ask, Prepare, Process, Analyze, Share, and Act.

Data Cleaning

# Convert date columns

daily$ActivityDate <- as.POSIXct(daily$ActivityDate, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
sleep$SleepDay <- as.POSIXct(sleep$SleepDay, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
weight$Date <- as.POSIXct(weight$Date, format = "%m/%d/%Y")

# Remove duplicates
sleep <- sleep %>% distinct()

# Remove nulls
weight <- weight %>% select(-Fat)

# Rename date columns and convert to Date class
daily <- rename(daily, date = ActivityDate)
sleep <- rename(sleep, date = SleepDay)
weight <- rename(weight, date = Date)

daily$date <- as.Date(daily$date)
sleep$date <- as.Date(sleep$date)
weight$date <- as.Date(weight$date)

Merging Datasets

daily_sleep <- merge(daily, sleep, by = c("Id", "date"))
daily_weight <- merge(daily, weight, by = c("Id", "date"))
sleep_weight <- merge(sleep, weight, by = c("Id", "date"))

Steps vs Calories

ggplot(data = daily, aes(TotalSteps, Calories)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Steps vs Calories Burned")

Users who walk more tend to burn more calories a strong positive relationship.

Steps vs Minutes Asleep

ggplot(daily_sleep, aes(TotalSteps, TotalMinutesAsleep)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  labs(title = "Steps vs Minutes Asleep")

Slight negative trend: as TotalSteps increase, sleep duration slightly decreases. Weak correlation.

Sleep Efficiency

sleep <- sleep %>% mutate(sleep_efficiency = TotalMinutesAsleep / TotalTimeInBed)
summary(sleep$sleep_efficiency)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.4984  0.9118  0.9426  0.9165  0.9606  1.0000
ggplot(sleep, aes(sleep_efficiency)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.05, fill = "steelblue", color = "white") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Sleep Efficiency", x = "Sleep Efficiency", y = "Count")

Most users have high sleep efficiency ( 0.9), while a smaller group shows low efficiency (< 0.8).

Sleep Efficiency by Weekday

sleep <- sleep %>% mutate(weekday = weekdays(date))
sleep$weekday <- factor(sleep$weekday, levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"))

sleep_eff_by_day <- sleep %>%
  group_by(weekday) %>%
  summarise(avg_efficiency = mean(sleep_efficiency, na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(sleep_eff_by_day, aes(x = weekday, y = avg_efficiency)) +
  geom_col(fill = "darkcyan") +
  labs(title = "Average Sleep Efficiency by Weekday", x = "Weekday", y = "Average Sleep Efficiency")

Sleep efficiency remains high across all days, with slight dips on weekends.

BMI vs Calories

ggplot(daily_weight, aes(BMI, Calories)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE, color = "blue") +
  labs(title = "BMI vs Calories Burned", x = "BMI", y = "Calories Burned")

Users with higher BMI may burn slightly more calories, but the relationship is weak and scattered.

Removing Outliers & Categorizing BMI

filtered_daily_weight <- daily_weight %>% filter(BMI >= 15, BMI <= 40)
filtered_daily_weight <- filtered_daily_weight %>% mutate(bmi_category = case_when(
  BMI < 18.5 ~ "Underweight",
  BMI < 25 ~ "Normal",
  BMI < 30 ~ "Overweight",
  TRUE ~ "Obese"
))

ggplot(filtered_daily_weight, aes(bmi_category, Calories, fill = bmi_category)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Calories Burned by BMI Category", x = "BMI Category", y = "Calories Burned") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2")

Overweight users burn more calories on average, with greater variability.

Weekly Activity Trends

daily <- daily %>% mutate(weekday = weekdays(date))
daily$weekday <- factor(daily$weekday, levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"))

weekday_steps <- daily %>% group_by(weekday) %>% summarise(avg_steps = mean(TotalSteps, na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(weekday_steps, aes(x = weekday, y = avg_steps)) +
  geom_col(fill = "steelblue") +
  labs(title = "Average Steps by Weekday", x = "Weekday", y = "Average Steps") +
  theme_minimal()

Users are most active on Mondays and Fridays, with noticeable drop-offs on weekends.

Final Recommendations

1. Capitalize on High-Activity Days

Users are most active on Mondays and Fridays, making these ideal days for motivational push notifications, in-app challenges, or promotional content. Positioning these days as Momentum Mondays or Fitness Fridays can reinforce healthy habits and boost engagement with Bellabeats products.

2. Support Users with Poor Sleep Efficiency

While most users have high sleep efficiency ( 0.9), a notable portion falls below 80%, indicating disrupted or restless sleep. Bellabeat should provide targeted support such as guided mindfulness sessions, bedtime reminders, or personalized sleep improvement suggestions through the app.

3. Personalize Activity Recommendations by BMI

Users with higher BMI tend to burn more calories, but also show greater variability. This suggests the need for tailored activity plans. Bellabeat can use this insight to offer adaptive coaching features that help these users build consistent, sustainable activity habits.

4. Address Weekend Activity Slumps

Step counts drop significantly on Saturdays and Sundays, highlighting an opportunity to engage users during weekends. Bellabeat can promote weekend-friendly wellness challenges, gentle movement routines, or hydration goals to help maintain momentum through the weekend.

5. Educate Users on Movement vs Rest
